# No Hardcoded Categories

The catalog has ~140 unique `articleType` values, ~45 unique `subCategory` values, and so on. These are derived from the actual cookbook dataset and **change** if the upstream pipeline reruns with different filtering. Any hardcoded list of categories in this codebase will silently drift out of sync with the data.

## Rule

The following lists must be derived from `catalog.json` at runtime, never written as literal arrays:

- `articleType` values (used in homepage filter pills, vision analysis prompt)
- `subCategory` values (used in results page grouping)
- `gender` values, `season` values, `usage` values, `baseColour` values

## Correct pattern

```typescript
import catalog from "@/data/catalog.json";

const articleTypes = useMemo(
  () => [...new Set(catalog.map((p) => p.articleType))].sort(),
  []
);
```

For the vision analysis prompt, pass the derived list in:

```typescript
const prompt = imageAnalysisPrompt(articleTypes);  // articleTypes from catalog
```

For the results page grouping, group by the matched products' actual `subCategory`:

```typescript
const grouped: Record<string, Product[]> = {};
for (const p of matchedProducts) {
  const key = p.subCategory || p.articleType;
  (grouped[key] ??= []).push(p);
}
```

## Anti-patterns

```typescript
// ❌ Hardcoded list
const CATEGORIES = ["Tshirts", "Shirts", "Casual Shoes", "Dresses"];

// ❌ Hardcoded vision prompt categories
const prompt = `... category must be one of: Tshirts, Shirts, Dresses ...`;

// ❌ Hardcoded result group order
const GROUP_ORDER = ["Topwear", "Bottomwear", "Footwear"];

// ❌ Hardcoded gender labels (the catalog uses "Men"/"Women" — match exactly)
const GENDERS = ["Male", "Female"];
```

## When in doubt

If you find yourself typing a category name as a string literal in any file other than `src/data/catalog.json`, stop. Derive it from catalog instead. The only exceptions are:

- The four valid `gender` values for the conversation system prompt's collected fields ("Women" | "Men")
- The four valid `season` values ("Summer" | "Winter" | "Fall" | "Spring")

These are intent-collection vocabulary, not catalog categories, and they're constrained by the `Intent` type in `src/types/index.ts`.
